The first half of History of Norwegian Literature covers texts and authors from medieval literature to mid-19th century romanticism. The topics studied are: medieval literature, baroque literature, literature of classicism and the Age of Enlightenment, folklore, folk tales and ballades, Norwegian writers in the so-called Danish period, national awakening, romanticism. 

The second half of History of Norwegian Literature covers texts and authors from late 19th century realism to present day. The topics studied are: realism, social realism, modernist developments (in poetry), literature of the interwar period, post-war literature, newer poetry, drama and prose.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of this course is to create a coherent system of literary and culture historical knowledge, as well as a timeline of Norwegian literature reaching from the Middle Ages to present day, introducing the main trends, epochs and significant authors. The course offers an opportunity to study the most accomplished works in Norwegian literature, which in turn contributes to a better understanding of the Norwegian society and culture in different time periods. The main focus is on reading and analysing different texts, complemented by compendious lectures and discussions on the periods being studied.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course, the student: - names and compares the main trends and developments in Norwegian literature from the Middle Ages to the second half of the 20th century; - names the most important authors and works in Norwegian literature from different periods; - analyses and compares different types of texts; - has read at least two Norwegian literary works and introduces them to others; - connects literary texts to the historical and societal background of the relevant period; - connects the significance of Norwegian literature to a broader context of world literature.
